{"key":"processedPost-11170020","value":{"id":11170020,"first":11136386,"last":11170020,"when":1254512784,"utime":"10/02/09 10:46 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>anonjon said:</strong><br />Yeah it does.<br /> Soak that long at higher temps and the seeds germinate.</blockquote><br />You should rinse the grains in hot tap water before the soak to remove dust, chaff, bugs, etc.&nbsp; The scalding hot tap water 'kills' the seeds, preventing germination during the soak.<br />Soaking longer than 24 hours at room temp can be counterproductive.&nbsp; Many endospores that germinate and grow will produce thousands of new endospores within a few hours.&nbsp; Since some of these nearly always survive pressure cooking, you could easily end up with more bacteria than you started with if you soak too long.&nbsp; I've found after a four to six hour soak, provided it was initiated with hot water, the grains have softened enough to be boiled without bursting the kernels.<br />RR","title":"Re: boiling grain"}}